<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA VOICES / A FORUM FOR COMMUNITY ISSUES: FAVORITE PLACES; 
BALLONA LAGOON COASTAL ACCESS PATH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ANN ARENS, Independent video producer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 "I take walks down the path by the Ballona Lagoon to the Marina del Rey 
Channel. It's good for when you need to get the blood flowing through your 
mind.There's some beautiful gardens and a lot of birds. The best thing is you 
see so many people, especially people walking their dogs. Everybody's really 
friendly, and you have a sense of a community. Dogs sort of break down the 
social barriers and you feel more open about starting conversations. " 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 The Ballona Lagoon Coastal Access Path is about a mile long, running from 
Washington Street to the Marina del Rey Channel and connecting to the newly 
restored Venice Canals. Ilene Weiss, president of the Ballona Lagoon Marine 
Preserve, says the path borders the only functioning tidal wetland in Los 
Angeles County. There are many species of crabs, clams, fish, and a wide 
variety of waterfowl and shorebirds, including the endangered least tern. For 
information, call (310) 306-5078.  
</P>
<P>
 Favorite Places columnist Jane Spiller welcomes suggestions for favorite 
places that are publicly accessible and free. Contact her c/o Voices.  
</P>
