<P>
OFF THE TICKER: RARE BANK NOTES, GOING, GOING . . . 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A collection of rare 19th-Century bank notes and printers' proofs goes on the 
block this week at Christie's. 
</P>
<P>
 The J.W. Middendorf II collection features notes issued by wildcat banks 
before the Civil War. The notes give vivid snapshots of the nation's past: 
</P>
<P>
 * A $100 note printed by the Bank of Rhode Island in Newport depicts the 
Battle of Bunker Hill. 
</P>
<P>
 * A $10 note from the Bank of Selma in Selma, Ala., pictures workers loading 
bales of cotton onto a wagon. 
</P>
<P>
 James Lamb of Christie's called the sale a natural move for a distinguished 
collector. 
</P>
<P>
 "A collector," he said, "having taken private pleasure from building it, wants 
some sort of recognition for having done it." 
</P>
