<P>
 Honda Gets Tough With Managers: The auto maker said it would start a tough new 
personnel policy threatening unproductive managers with demotion and pay cuts, 
a move analysts said is part of a broader trend whittling away at Japan's 
once-vaunted lifetime employment system. Under Honda Motor Co.'s new program, 
managers who fail to win promotion within eight to 12 years will be demoted and 
their salaries cut 10% to 30%, a Honda spokesman said. Honda's move echoes 
changes at other car companies which, faced with weak demand and overcapacity, 
are struggling to cut costs, improve management flexibility and link pay 
packets more closely to performance rather than seniority alone. 
